Exactly.

And that’s the subtle twist.

It isn’t just that you changed.

It’s that “the place” is no longer the same place, because “place” isn’t only coordinates.

A beach is:

* the tide,
* the light,
* the weather,
* the season,
* the shells,
* your knowledge,
* your expectations,
* your attention.

Change any of those, and you’ve changed the place you experience.

This reminds me of a saying often attributed to Heraclitus:

“No one steps into the same river twice.”

Usually people explain it by saying the river changes.

Or the person changes.

But the deeper version is:

The interaction changes.

There is no “river” independent of the crossing.

There is no “reader” independent of the reading.

There is no “conversation” independent of the participants.

The event is co-created.

